100 days being present. My last day drinking was August 30th. I blacked out by 6pm and couldn’t get my keys in the front door. I would regularly drink every day starting at noon until whenever I went to bed. I prided myself on out drinking anyone. My identity was tied to alcohol almost as much as it was being an artist. These last few months have provided me with an immense amount of clarity. A few things are certain, I am becoming a better husband, father and artist without my dependency on booze.
Some recent photos in my studio by @harrisonboyce
Big noodle painting in the studio.
Named as one of the 100 most influential creatives in the world. Thank you @hypebeast🥇We’re still just getting started 💫
I have realized being a Dad is a great privilege. I always want to show up for my daughter, she deserves my heart and my time. I love you Fifi.
Poking the bear. Making paintings about New York — in Detroit.

A week from tomorrow my solo exhibition titled 𝓢𝓽𝓮𝓪𝓵𝓲𝓷𝓰 𝓢𝓲𝓰𝓷𝓼 opens in South Korea @ganaart_seoul curated by @mattblackstudio 💫💫💫

𝓢𝓽𝓪𝓻 𝓞𝓷 𝓣𝓱𝓮 𝓡𝓲𝓼𝓮 (𝓑𝓾𝓽 𝓨𝓸𝓾 𝓐𝓵𝓻𝓮𝓪𝓭𝔂 𝓚𝓷𝓮𝔀 𝓣𝓱𝓪𝓽) (2022). Jet lag is kicking my ass right now but greatly looking forward to my opening this coming week @ganaart_seoul curated by @mattblackstudio 

As this exhibition kicks off a packed 2023 for me I have been thinking a lot about how exciting life is. I’d say excitement is typically perceived as corny in the art world. But I don’t care. Excitement is cool! I get to travel all over the world exhibiting my art. I’m not going to be chill about that lol. I’M LIVING MY DREAM 💫

Tomorrow 𝓢𝓽𝓮𝓪𝓵𝓲𝓷𝓰 𝓢𝓲𝓰𝓷𝓼 opens @ganaart_seoul // this show’s title has a very special meaning to me as it was the working title for a 2-person exhibition with a friend of mine who has since passed away.

I’ve learned so much from those who have come before me. And my work (these sculptures in particular) acknowledge art history’s impact on most everything I do. I’m an honest thief 😏 Buckle up. See you tomorrow!

Responding to sports history by contributing to art history. Tell me another artist who has taken the autograph to the place that I continuously am. I’ll wait.

As the great bowler Pete Weber once said, “Hate me or love me, you watched. That’s all you could do.”

I made this painting this morning in one straight shot. I love watching greatness. Witnessing Lebron’s career has been nothing short of amazing. Excellence in sports is something that motivates me tremendously in my own work.

Good morning Hong Kong. Yesterday was a dream come true. It’s really amazing to see my own dreams come true. I’ve been filled with so much gratitude lately for all of the people who have helped me realize and manifest these dreams. Only thing missing right now is @coco______winston_ and my sweet baby girl, Fifi. I’d like to remind you all I’m just getting started and I’m the fucking best 🥇💫

Ben and I have been friends for years and have had many a late night conversation while smoking outside of random bars and restaurants all over the world. This collection was designed as a nod to the museum store and these single cigarette holders are souvenirs to commemorate our friendship. Edition of 50.

Milano! What a week! I didn’t leave the country until I was 25. As my career started to takeoff I told myself that when I have kids I am going to make a point to have them travel around the world with me as much as possible. Helaena will most likely never remember this trip (she is 19 months) but it’s my hope that these travels that she’s experiencing at such a young age subconsciously expand her cultural horizons and stay with her in some capacity for a very long time 💙

Today I feel larger than life. Maybe it has to do with the fact that I’ve been working on a large scale series of blue punishment works of figures who are larger than life? I watched “Air” yesterday and couldn’t help but think of the power of belief in one’s self and vision, regardless of if the world initially sees it or understands it. It’s such an in incredible privilege to get to make work that I believe in every single day.

I’ll be in Athens, Greece for the week for the opening of my solo exhibition 𝓝𝓮𝔀 𝓡𝓮𝓵𝓲𝓰𝓲𝓸𝓷, 𝓣𝓻𝓾𝓮 𝓡𝓮𝓵𝓲𝓰𝓲𝓸𝓷, 𝓑𝓲𝓰𝓰𝓮𝓻 𝓣𝓱𝓪𝓷 𝓣𝓱𝓮 𝓟𝓸𝓹𝓮 - there are some surprises in store 💫

My first bronze sculpture 𝓘𝓶𝓹𝓸𝓼𝓽𝓮𝓻 𝓢𝔂𝓷𝓭𝓻𝓸𝓶𝓮 part of 𝓝𝓮𝔀 𝓡𝓮𝓵𝓲𝓰𝓲𝓸𝓷, 𝓣𝓻𝓾𝓮 𝓡𝓮𝓵𝓲𝓰𝓲𝓸𝓷, 𝓑𝓲𝓰𝓰𝓮𝓻 𝓣𝓱𝓪𝓷 𝓣𝓱𝓮 𝓟𝓸𝓹𝓮 opening preview tonight and public opening on Saturday @allouche_benias_gallery 

A little about this sculpture, the stool with the basketball rim is a motif I’ve explored for a few years. It’s always been an ode to Marcel Duchamp'”Bicycle Wheel”. This sculpture in particular is a nod to Sherrie Levine's “Fountain (Buddha)”. It extends conversations around the influence of their work on artists such as myself, this is a championship trophy of sorts -- Its title 𝓘𝓶𝓹𝓸𝓼𝓽𝓮𝓻 𝓢𝔂𝓷𝓭𝓻𝓸𝓶𝓮 is an acknowledgement of my using references and feeling comfortably uncomfortable about them. It's akin to an athlete taking a move from another athlete they admire and making it their own, having it become part of their game.

All I can say is @aimeleondore made the most insane leather jacket for me. All of the patches reference my work. We made a beautiful collection together to coincide with the opening of my first show in Greece. Available soon 🖤

Jewelry collection with @aimeleondore 💫💫💫 If you know me, you know I love jewelry. Hard to pick a favorite piece but the “Champion That Nobody Cares About” championship ring is up there. The quote refers to a 1986 Issue of Sports Illustrated that I’ve referenced in my art a number of times with tennis great Ivan Lendl on the cover. He had just won the US Open and nobody seemed to care. 

Furthermore, a gigantic thank you to everyone @aimeleondore who worked on this project. You guys are like family to me and it has been truly special to grow with the brand and to have this all come together ❤️

The first painting is of Dan Marino’s autograph titled, 𝓕𝓲𝓷𝓼 𝓤𝓹 (2023), the second, Lionel Messi’s autograph titled, 𝓑𝓪𝓼𝓴𝓮𝓽𝓫𝓪𝓵𝓵 𝓓𝓲𝓪𝓻𝓲𝓮𝓼, 𝓑𝓾𝓽 𝓝𝓸𝓽 𝓡𝓮𝓪𝓵𝓵𝔂 (2023).

In the course of art history there has never been an artist who is examining, dissecting, exploring the autograph/signature in the way that I am. It’s okay that these are misunderstood/scoffed at/ridiculed/written off as bastard Twombly work/etc.

A gallerist recently asked me when I would stop making them, my response — I’ve only just begun.

I love to paint. I never thought I would, but I do. I have no idea or plan for what any of these punishment paintings look like ahead of time. There is no outline, no map, it’s instinct. I have come to find a great joy in the unknown.
